al (human/demi-human/humanoid-like) creatures of Medium size or smaller.\n    Each target saves vs spells and applies its Wisdom save modifier (if any), plus a modifier based on targets chosen:\n        1 target: saves at -2\n        2 targets: no modifier\n        3 targets: each saves at +2\n    Held creatures cannot move voluntary muscles, but may keep breathing and heartbeat continues. Psychic/psionic powers usable without voluntary movement may still function.\nCombat effects (paralysis reminder):\n    Held creatures are physically helpless. If you have a hand weapon and are not in melee, you can automatically kill one held creature each round.\n    If you have rope/chain/bindings and are not in melee, you may bind one held creature each round instead of attacking.\n    You may choose normal attacks instead (e.g., still in melee, multiple attacks, touch spell).\n    Any weapon/unarmed/touch attack against a held creature hits automatically unless you choose to miss. On a hit with a weapon/unarmed attack, you may deal maximum damage instead of rolling. If every creature you attack is held, your number of attacks is doubled that round.", "link": ""}, "know alignment": {"name": "Know Alignment", "level": "2", "school": "Divine divination", "range": "Caster", "duration": "1 turn", "aoe": "1 creature, object, or place per round", "components": "V, S, M", "ct": "1 round", "save": "None", "save_type": "", "description": "After casting, you may focus on one target per round within 10 ft and learn its alignment.\nDetails:\n    Reveals alignment, not danger; it won’t necessarily reveal traps or poison.\n    Does not necessarily detect curses, though some horrific curses can make an item inherently evil (typically neutral evil).\n    Opaque materials interfere: penetrates metal up to 1 inch, and brick/stone up to 1 foot.\n    Most places do not have alignments, except certain sites (e.g., temples, desecrated temples, outer-planar portals, and places specifically described as good/evil/holy/unholy).\nReversible as Conceal Alignment:", "notes": "After casting, you may focus on one target per round within 10 ft and learn its alignment.\nDetails:\n    Reveals alignment, not danger; it won’t necessarily reveal traps or poison.\n    Does not necessarily detect curses, though some horrific curses can make an item inherently evil (typically neutral evil).\n    Opaque materials interfere: penetrates metal up to 1 inch, and brick/stone up to 1 foot.\n    Most places do not have alignments, except certain sites (e.g., temples, desecrated temples, outer-planar portals, and places specifically described as good/evil/holy/unholy).\nReversible as Conceal Alignment:", "link": ""}, "resist fire": {"name": "Resist Fire", "level": "2", "school": "Divine abjuration", "range": "Touch", "duration": "1 turn per cleric level", "aoe": "1 creature", "components": "V, S, M", "ct": "1 round", "save": "None", "save_type": "", "description": "Protects the target against fire damage and heat.\nDetails:\n    Safe from non-magical fire (e.g., torches).\n    Immune to ill effects of normal heat (up to boiling).\n    Against magical or extremely hot fire, grants:\n        Provides Saving Throw: May attempt a saving throw against any magical fire effect even if none is normally allowed (typically vs spells and other magical effects).\n        Improves Saving Throw: If already allowed a save vs fire damage, may choose to add +3.\n        Reduces Damage: Fire damage is halved; if already halved (e.g., successful save), halve again. Round down.", "notes": "Protects the target against fire damage and heat.\nDetails:\n    Safe from non-magical fire (e.g., torches).\n    Immune to ill effects of normal heat (up to boiling).\n    Against magical or extremely hot fire, grants:\n        Provides Saving Throw: May attempt a saving throw against any magical fire effect even if none is normally allowed (typically vs spells and other magical effects).\n        Improves Saving Throw: If already allowed a save vs fire damage, may choose to add +3.\n        Reduces Damage: Fire damage is halved; if already halved (e.g., successful save), halve again. Round down.", "link": ""}, "silence 15 ft radius": {"name": "Silence 15 Ft Radius", "level": "2", "school": "Divine transmutation", "range": "120 ft", "duration": "2 rounds per cleric level", "aoe": "15 ft radius sphere around the target", "components": "V, S", "ct": "5 segments", "save": "See below", "save_type": "", "description": "Creates a zone of silence centred on a creature, object, or point in space. Within the area:\n    No sound can be produced; and\n    No sound can be heard, even from outside the zone.\nDetails:\n    Objects and points in space receive no saving throw.\n    A creature target may choose a saving throw vs spells and other magical effects:\n        Success: the target becomes the 5 ft square the creature is standing in (the creature can move out).\n        Failure: the creature remains the target; the silence moves with it.\n    Combat effects:\n        No one can cast spells with a verbal component within the area.\n        Attempts to sneak or move quietly always succeed if the creature is within the area.\n        Echolocation-dependent creatures (e.g., bats, dolphins) are blinded and suffer -4 “to hit”.", "notes": "Creates a zone of silence centred on a creature, object, or point in space. Within the area:\n    No sound can be produced; and\n    No sound can be heard, even from outside the zone.\nDetails:\n    Objects and points in space receive no saving throw.\n    A creature target may choose a saving throw vs spells and other magical effects:\n        Success: the target becomes the 5 ft square the creature is standing in (the creature can move out).\n        Failure: the creature remains the target; the silence moves with it.\n    Combat effects:\n        No one can cast spells with a verbal component within the area.\n        Attempts to sneak or move quietly always succeed if the creature is within the area.\n        Echolocation-dependent creatures (e.g., bats, dolphins) are blinded and suffer -4 “to hit”.", "link": ""}, "slow poison": {"name": "Slow Poison", "level": "2", "school": "Divine necromancy", "range": "Touch", "duration": "6 turns per cleric level", "aoe": "1 creature", "components": "V, S, M", "ct": "Fast", "save": "None", "save_type": "", "description": "Slows the effects of poison to keep someone alive until the poison can be neutralised (e.g., antidote or neutralise poison).\nDetails:\nPoison is often treated as “save or die,” but death is not instantaneous. This spell can slow poison and keep a victim alive within a time window determined by cleric level.\n    Target poisoned but not dead:\n    Record poison damage taken at the moment of casting; this is “slowed damage.”\n    Slowed damage is healed immediately when the spell is cast.\n    During the duration, the creature takes 1 hp poison damage every 10 rounds, but cannot be reduced below 1 hp by this poison damage until the spell ends.\n    Other (non-poison) damage applies normally.\n    Target recently dead from poison:\n    A creature counts as “recently died of poison” if it died from poison damage or from failing a save vs poison within a number of turns equal to your cleric level.\n    The creature is restored to life at the hit points it had before the poison affected it.\n    During the duration, it takes 1 hp poison damage every 10 rounds, but cannot be reduced below 1 hp by this poison damage until the spell ends.\n    Other damage applies normally.\nAdditional poison during duration:\n    Additional poison damage is not applied immediately; record it as additional slowed damage.\n    If the creature fails further saves vs poison, those poison effects are also delayed until the spell ends.\n    If the poison is not cured by the time the spell expires, all slowed poisons take full effect immediately, including the full amount of slowed damage.", "notes": "Slows the effects of poison to keep someone alive until the poison can be neutralised (e.g., antidote or neutralise poison).\nDetails:\nPoison is often treated as “save or die,” but death is not instantaneous. This spell can slow poison and keep a victim alive within a time window determined by cleric level.\n    Target poisoned but not dead:\n    Record poison damage taken at the moment of casting; this is “slowed damage.”\n    Slowed damage is healed immediately when the spell is cast.\n    During the duration, the creature takes 1 hp poison damage every 10 rounds, but cannot be reduced below 1 hp by this poison damage until the spell ends.\n    Other (non-poison) damage applies normally.\n    Target recently dead from poison:\n    A creature counts as “recently died of poison” if it died from poison damage or from failing a save vs poison within a number of turns equal to your cleric level.\n    The creature is restored to life at the hit points it had before the poison affected it.\n    During the duration, it takes 1 hp poison damage every 10 rounds, but cannot be reduced below 1 hp by this poison damage until the spell ends.\n    Other damage applies normally.\nAdditional poison during duration:\n    Additional poison damage is not applied immediately; record it as additional slowed damage.\n    If the creature fails further saves vs poison, those poison effects are also delayed until the spell ends.\n    If the poison is not cured by the time the spell expires, all slowed poisons take full effect immediately, including the full amount of slowed damage.", "link": ""}, "snake charm": {"name": "Snake Charm", "level": "2", "school": "Divine enchantment", "range": "30 ft", "duration": "2 rounds per cleric level", "aoe": "One animal within range", "components": "V, S", "ct": "5 segments", "save": "None", "save_type": "", "description": "Affects snakes, serpents, couatls, nagas, and other ophidian/serpentine creatures: they rear up and sway without otherwise moving, taking no actions and not attacking until the spell ends. When it ends, they forget what occurred while affected.\nDetails:\n    Total hit points of affected creatures cannot exceed your uninjured hit points. If you target more, the GM decides (or randomly determines) which are unaffected until the total affected hp is within your limit.\n    If in doubt, affected creatures include those listed above and other reptilian creatures that had no limbs when hatched. Not affected: dragons, demons, devils, wyverns.\n        Asleep/unconscious: 1d4 + 2 turns\n        Alert: 1d3 turns\n        Angry/attacking: 1d4 + 4 rounds\n    Attacking a charmed snake breaks the charm on that snake only.\nSPEAK WITH ANIMALS\nClerical transmutation, level 2\nAllows communication with a nearby animal.\nDetails:\n    You speak in Common; the animal understands magically. The animal communicates in its natural way; meaning is translated into your mind (others do not hear the translation).\n    You may attempt persuasion, deception, or bargaining for services.\n    Affects normal non-fantastic animals (wolves, badgers, bears) and giant versions without additional fantastic abilities (e.g., giant lizard yes; basilisk no).\n    Mindless animals (INT “non” or 0) are not affected. The animal must have intelligence of animal, semi-, or low.\n    Humans are not animals for this spell.\n    The spell does not compel truth, and it does not force the animal to stop fighting if you/your allies attacked it, though it usually won’t initiate combat while the spell is in effect.", "notes": "Affects snakes, serpents, couatls, nagas, and other ophidian/serpentine creatures: they rear up and sway without otherwise moving, taking no actions and not attacking until the spell ends. When it ends, they forget what occurred while affected.\nDetails:\n    Total hit points of affected creatures cannot exceed your uninjured hit points. If you target more, the GM decides (or randomly determines) which are unaffected until the total affected hp is within your limit.\n    If in doubt, affected creatures include those listed above and other reptilian creatures that had no limbs when hatched. Not affected: dragons, demons, devils, wyverns.\n        Asleep/unconscious: 1d4 + 2 turns\n        Alert: 1d3 turns\n        Angry/attacking: 1d4 + 4 rounds\n    Attacking a charmed snake breaks the charm on that snake only.\nSPEAK WITH ANIMALS\nClerical transmutation, level 2\nAllows communication with a nearby animal.\nDetails:\n    You speak in Common; the animal understands magically. The animal communicates in its natural way; meaning is translated into your mind (others do not hear the translation).\n    You may attempt persuasion, deception, or bargaining for services.\n    Affects normal non-fantastic animals (wolves, badgers, bears) and giant versions without additional fantastic abilities (e.g., giant lizard yes; basilisk no).\n    Mindless animals (INT “non” or 0) are not affected. The animal must have intelligence of animal, semi-, or low.\n    Humans are not animals for this spell.\n    The spell does not compel truth, and it does not force the animal to stop fighting if you/your allies attacked it, though it usually won’t initiate combat while the spell is in effect.", "link": ""}, "spiritual weapon": {"name": "Spiritual Weapon", "level": "2", "school": "Divine conjuration", "range": "30 ft", "duration": "1 round per cleric level", "aoe": "30 ft radius around you", "components": "V, S, M", "ct": "5 segments", "save": "None", "save_type": "", "description": "Creates a magical force shaped like a weapon (usually a hammer; may match your deity’s sacred weapon). It cannot move more than 30 ft from you, but within that radius it attacks where you direct it.\nDetails:\n    Each round until the spell ends, you may attack one creature within range using the spiritual weapon. Roll to hit as if using a regular weapon.\n    On a hit, it deals 1d6 magical damage (not blunt/piercing/slashing; can harm creatures immune to mundane weapons, and isn’t treated as a “weapon” for those purposes).\n    The weapon is not physical and can pass through obstacles (including walls) as long as it stays within the area.\n    If you direct it to attack a target you can’t see, you are effectively blinded with respect to that target.\n    If it attacks from behind, it gains the normal rear-attack bonus (usually +2).\n    You must concentrate to maintain the spell, or it ends (see Concentration rules).", "notes": "Creates a magical force shaped like a weapon (usually a hammer; may match your deity’s sacred weapon). It cannot move more than 30 ft from you, but within that radius it attacks where you direct it.\nDetails:\n    Each round until the spell ends, you may attack one creature within range using the spiritual weapon. Roll to hit as if using a regular weapon.\n    On a hit, it deals 1d6 magical damage (not blunt/piercing/slashing; can harm creatures immune to mundane weapons, and isn’t treated as a “weapon” for those purposes).\n    The weapon is not physical and can pass through obstacles (including walls) as long as it stays within the area.\n    If you direct it to attack a target you can’t see, you are effectively blinded with respect to that target.\n    If it attacks from behind, it gains the normal rear-attack bonus (usually +2).\n    You must concentrate to maintain the spell, or it ends (see Concentration rules).", "link": ""}, "animate dead": {"name": "Animate Dead", "level": "3", "school": "Divine necromancy", "range": "10 ft", "duration": "Instantaneous", "aoe": "Up to 1 corpse per cleric level", "components": "V, S, M", "ct": "1 round", "save": "None", "save_type": "", "description": "You animate dead bodies to serve you. The undead created are skeletons or zombies, depending on decomposition. Larger undead can be created, but doing so reduces the total number of “corpses” you can affect (see below).\nDetails:\n    The undead obey simple verbal commands. They understand any spoken language. Control cannot be delegated (you can’t order them to follow someone else’s orders), though you can specify actions that trigger when another person says something.\n    You can’t animate a corpse that is already undead.\n    If not commanded, undead do nothing. They feel no pain or fear, have no self-preservation, and do not defend themselves while idle.\n    Commands must be loud, clear, completely unambiguous, and require no deduction or interpretation. Example: “Attack the elf in the blue robe” works; “Attack the wizard” may not (too much deduction). If the command is ambiguous (e.g., two elves in blue robes), they do nothing.\n    Animated undead cannot perceive creatures more than 60 ft away.\n    After completing a command, they do nothing until commanded again.\n    If you issue no commands for 7 consecutive days, they become free-willed skeletons/zombies. Free-willed undead defend themselves and typically attack any living creatures larger than an insect they can perceive. Over time, they drift toward dark places and sites of evil deeds.\nMonster type:\n    Human / demi-human / humanoid corpses: Rise as zombies, or as skeletons if bones are mostly exposed. They fight as standard zombies/skeletons. They can use hand weapons if available. Zombies cannot use bows/crossbows/slings, but can use thrown weapons. Skeletons can use missile weapons without restriction.\n    Roughly human-sized but not human-like in shape: Rise as animal skeletons/zombies. They cannot use weapons and can only move by walking (no flight, even if the corpse had wings).\n    Human-like but larger than human: Rise as mighty skeletons/zombies with the hit dice they had in life. Each additional hit die beyond 1 counts as an additional “corpse” for this spell’s limit. Example: at cleric level 9, you could raise an 8 HD hill giant zombie plus one other human-sized corpse.\n    Larger than human and not human-like in shape: Cannot be animated by this spell (e.g., dragon skeleton).\nSetting note: Many good-aligned religions forbid this spell; others allow it only in dire need. In most civilised lands, casting it and controlling undead are criminal acts.", "notes": "You animate dead bodies to serve you. The undead created are skeletons or zombies, depending on decomposition. Larger undead can be created, but doing so reduces the total number of “corpses” you can affect (see below).\nDetails:\n    The undead obey simple verbal commands. They understand any spoken language. Control cannot be delegated (you can’t order them to follow someone else’s orders), though you can specify actions that trigger when another person says something.\n    You can’t animate a corpse that is already undead.\n    If not commanded, undead do nothing. They feel no pain or fear, have no self-preservation, and do not defend themselves while idle.\n    Commands must be loud, clear, completely unambiguous, and require no deduction or interpretation. Example: “Attack the elf in the blue robe” works; “Attack the wizard” may not (too much deduction). If the command is ambiguous (e.g., two elves in blue robes), they do nothing.\n    Animated undead cannot perceive creatures more than 60 ft away.\n    After completing a command, they do nothing until commanded again.\n    If you issue no commands for 7 consecutive days, they become free-willed skeletons/zombies. Free-willed undead defend themselves and typically attack any living creatures larger than an insect they can perceive. Over time, they drift toward dark places and sites of evil deeds.\nMonster type:\n    Human / demi-human / humanoid corpses: Rise as zombies, or as skeletons if bones are mostly exposed. They fight as standard zombies/skeletons. They can use hand weapons if available. Zombies cannot use bows/crossbows/slings, but can use thrown weapons. Skeletons can use missile weapons without restriction.\n    Roughly human-sized but not human-like in shape: Rise as animal skeletons/zombies. They cannot use weapons and can only move by walking (no flight, even if the corpse had wings).\n    Human-like but larger than human: Rise as mighty skeletons/zombies with the hit dice they had in life. Each additional hit die beyond 1 counts as an additional “corpse” for this spell’s limit. Example: at cleric level 9, you could raise an 8 HD hill giant zombie plus one other human-sized corpse.\n    Larger than human and not human-like in shape: Cannot be animated by this spell (e.g., dragon skeleton).\nSetting note: Many good-aligned religions forbid this spell; others allow it only in dire need. In most civilised lands, casting it and controlling undead are criminal acts.", "link": ""}, "bestow curse": {"name": "Bestow Curse", "level": "3", "school": "Divine conjuration", "range": "Touch", "duration": "Instantaneous", "aoe": "1 creature", "components": "V, S", "ct": "6 segments", "save": "Yes (negates effect)", "save_type": "", "description": "Places a curse on the target.\nDetails:\n    A creature can only be affected by one instance of this spell at a time.\n    Many good-aligned religions forbid this spell; others allow it only in dire need.\n    On a successful curse, roll 1d8:\nRoll\tEffect\n1–4\tOne ability score reduced to 3\n5–6\t-4 to attack rolls and saving throws\n7–8\tClumsy: each round, 50% chance to drop each held object; if holding nothing, 50% chance it can’t act that round\nThe curse remains until removed by remove curse, dispelled, or revoked by the caster.\nOptional rule: some religions may have alternative curses (cult secrets, lost secrets, forbidden secrets), learned through donations, service, research, extraplanar consultation, or major quests (GM decides availability and effects).", "notes": "Places a curse on the target.\nDetails:\n    A creature can only be affected by one instance of this spell at a time.\n    Many good-aligned religions forbid this spell; others allow it only in dire need.\n    On a successful curse, roll 1d8:\nRoll\tEffect\n1–4\tOne ability score reduced to 3\n5–6\t-4 to attack rolls and saving throws\n7–8\tClumsy: each round, 50% chance to drop each held object; if holding nothing, 50% chance it can’t act that round\nThe curse remains until removed by remove curse, dispelled, or revoked by the caster.\nOptional rule: some religions may have alternative curses (cult secrets, lost secrets, forbidden secrets), learned through donations, service, research, extraplanar consultation, or major quests (GM decides availability and effects).", "link": ""}, "cause blindness": {"name": "Cause Blindness", "level": "3", "school": "Divine transmutation", "range": "Touch", "duration": "Permanent", "aoe": "Creature touched", "components": "V, S", "ct": "8 segments", "save": "Yes (negates effect)", "save_type": "", "description": "Causes a target to become blind until removed by the caster, dispelled, or cured by cure blindness.\nDetails:\n    If you miss the to-hit roll, the spell is lost.\n    Affects only living creatures (not undead) and has no effect on creatures that do not rely on vision.\n    Many good-aligned religions forbid this spell; others allow it only in dire need.", "notes": "Causes a target to become blind until removed by the caster, dispelled, or cured by cure blindness.\nDetails:\n    If you miss the to-hit roll, the spell is lost.\n    Affects only living creatures (not undead) and has no effect on creatures that do not rely on vision.\n    Many good-aligned religions forbid this spell; others allow it only in dire need.", "link": ""}, "cause disease": {"name": "Cause Disease", "level": "3", "school": "Divine transmutation", "range": "Touch", "duration": "Permanent", "aoe": "Creature touched", "components": "V, S", "ct": "10 rounds", "save": "Negates effect", "save_type": "", "description": "Infects the target with a disease.\nDetails:\n    Requires touch (to-hit roll if resisting and not immobilised). Even on a successful touch, the target saves vs spells;