r as curing underlying pathology/parasites helps.\n    Affects only normally living creatures; no effect on constructs, elementals, golems, undead.\n    Cures lycanthropy only if cast before the first transformation. After first change, lycanthropy becomes a mixed disease/curse/magical alteration.\n    The target may choose a saving throw vs spells and other effects; on a success, one or more diseases of its choice are not cured.\n    Has certain special uses that cure non-disease effects in specific OSRIC creature/object entries.\nReversible as Cause Disease:", "link": ""}, "dispel magic": {"name": "Dispel Magic", "level": "3", "school": "Divine abjuration", "range": "60 ft", "duration": "Instantaneous", "aoe": "30 ft radius sphere", "components": "V, S", "ct": "6 segments", "save": "No (but see below for failure chance)", "save_type": "", "description": "Removes or suppresses magical effects in the area. The centre point may be a creature, object, place, or point in space within range.\nDetails:\n    Gods, demigods, artifacts, relics, and equivalent powers are not affected.\n    Psychic/psionic powers are not magical and are not affected.\n    When casting completes:\n        Any ongoing spell effects in the area that you personally cast end.\n        If a creature in the area is currently casting a spell, that spell is interrupted.\n    Then, for each dispellable magical effect in the area, the GM rolls d100 (often in secret). Success chance depends on caster levels:\n        If your cleric level is ≥ the effect’s caster level: 50% + 5% per level difference.\n        If your cleric level is < the effect’s caster level: 50% - 2% per level difference.\n        For potions/scrolls, caster level is 12 unless creation required higher; then use the minimum level to create it (e.g., time stop scroll is caster level 18).\n    On a successful dispel of an effect:\n        Spell effects wholly within the area end (including innate spell-like powers and item-cast spell effects).\n        If only partly overlapped, the spell does not end, but the overlapped portion is suppressed for 1 hour.\n        Potions/scrolls are denatured (potions become inert liquid; scrolls become blank).\n        Permanent magic items have their powers suppressed for 1 round (become non-magical for that round).\n        Constructs/elementals/golems/summoned creatures are not banished, but may temporarily lose spell/spell-like powers; such powers return after 1d6 rounds.", "notes": "Removes or suppresses magical effects in the area. The centre point may be a creature, object, place, or point in space within range.\nDetails:\n    Gods, demigods, artifacts, relics, and equivalent powers are not affected.\n    Psychic/psionic powers are not magical and are not affected.\n    When casting completes:\n        Any ongoing spell effects in the area that you personally cast end.\n        If a creature in the area is currently casting a spell, that spell is interrupted.\n    Then, for each dispellable magical effect in the area, the GM rolls d100 (often in secret). Success chance depends on caster levels:\n        If your cleric level is ≥ the effect’s caster level: 50% + 5% per level difference.\n        If your cleric level is < the effect’s caster level: 50% - 2% per level difference.\n        For potions/scrolls, caster level is 12 unless creation required higher; then use the minimum level to create it (e.g., time stop scroll is caster level 18).\n    On a successful dispel of an effect:\n        Spell effects wholly within the area end (including innate spell-like powers and item-cast spell effects).\n        If only partly overlapped, the spell does not end, but the overlapped portion is suppressed for 1 hour.\n        Potions/scrolls are denatured (potions become inert liquid; scrolls become blank).\n        Permanent magic items have their powers suppressed for 1 round (become non-magical for that round).\n        Constructs/elementals/golems/summoned creatures are not banished, but may temporarily lose spell/spell-like powers; such powers return after 1d6 rounds.", "link": ""}, "feign death": {"name": "Feign Death", "level": "3", "school": "Divine necromancy", "range": "Touch", "duration": "10 rounds + 1 round per cleric level", "aoe": "Creature touched", "components": "V, S, M", "ct": "Fast", "save": "None", "save_type": "", "description": "The target becomes corpse-like, enabling it to “play dead,” and gains protection from certain harms.\nDetails:\n    Only affects willing creatures. You or the target may end the spell at any time.\n    While affected:\n        No need to eat, drink, breathe, or sleep.\n        Can hear, smell, and think, but is blinded and loses sense of touch. Feels no pain and does not know when injured.\n        Immune to undead touch attacks; cannot be poisoned; cannot contract disease. Existing poison is suspended during the spell and returns afterward.\n        Damage from other sources is halved (round down).\n    When the spell ends, the target needs 1 round to stand and recover.", "notes": "The target becomes corpse-like, enabling it to “play dead,” and gains protection from certain harms.\nDetails:\n    Only affects willing creatures. You or the target may end the spell at any time.\n    While affected:\n        No need to eat, drink, breathe, or sleep.\n        Can hear, smell, and think, but is blinded and loses sense of touch. Feels no pain and does not know when injured.\n        Immune to undead touch attacks; cannot be poisoned; cannot contract disease. Existing poison is suspended during the spell and returns afterward.\n        Damage from other sources is halved (round down).\n    When the spell ends, the target needs 1 round to stand and recover.", "link": ""}, "glyph of warding": {"name": "Glyph of Warding", "level": "3", "school": "Divine evocation", "range": "Touch", "duration": "Until discharged", "aoe": "Up to 25 sq. ft per cleric level", "components": "V, S, M", "ct": "1 segment per sq. ft protected", "save": "When activated (save for half)", "save_type": "", "description": "You inscribe an invisible glyph on a solid surface. It remains invisible unless detect magic is used. A “forbidden creature” (as defined at casting) discharges the glyph when it performs a defined triggering action.\nDetails:\n    You must define:\n        A forbidden creature (e.g., “any living being,” “anyone but myself,” “a dwarf,” “Richard the Necrophage,” etc.).\n        A triggering action (typically opening a warded door or passing through a warded area).\n        The exact area to be warded.\n    When triggered, each creature in the area may save vs spells/spell-like effects:\n        Success: half damage and may disregard other glyph effects (if any).\n    You must know the specific glyph you’re using. Fire/lightning/ice/acid glyphs are secrets of clerical orders; blindness/paralysis are lost secrets; drain/petrify/banish are long-lost and widely forbidden, requiring major effort/quests to learn.\n    If warding more than 50 sq. ft, gems worth 2,000 gp must be destroyed as a material component.\n    You can only use glyph types permitted by your cleric level:\nMinimum Cleric Level\tGlyph\tNoise\tEffect\n3\tFire\tNoisy\t2 hp fire damage per cleric level\n5\tLightning\tLoud\t2 hp lightning damage per cleric level\n7\tIce\tQuiet\t2 hp cold damage per cleric level\n9\tAcid\tQuiet\t2 hp corrosion damage per cleric level\n11\tBlindness\tSilent\tSave or blinded for 3d6 rounds\n13\tParalysis\tSilent\tSave or paralysed for 2d6 rounds\n15\tDrain\tSilent\tSave or lose 1 life energy level\n17\tPetrify\tSilent\tSave or turned to stone\n20\tBanish\tSilent\tSave or sent to deity-associated plane", "notes": "You inscribe an invisible glyph on a solid surface. It remains invisible unless detect magic is used. A “forbidden creature” (as defined at casting) discharges the glyph when it performs a defined triggering action.\nDetails:\n    You must define:\n        A forbidde